04400nam a22007095i 9780231520973DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2009030127  a(OCoLC)1013944528  a97802315209737 a10.7312/hols150422doi  a(DE-B1597)458945  a(OCoLC)979683089  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJZ1734.A57bI4 2010 7aPOL0110002bisacsh1 aHolslag, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChina and India :bProspects for Peace /cJonathan Holslag. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b11 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Asia in the World00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntro. Sino-Indian Rivalry in an Era of Globalization -- tOne. Emerging Trading States -- tTwo. The Evolution of Sino-Indian Relations -- tThree. Ricardo’s Reality -- tFour. Shifting Perceptions -- tFive. The Military Security Dilemma -- tSix. Regional Security Cooperation -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor all their spectacular growth, China and India must still lift a hundred million citizens out of poverty and create jobs for the numerous laborers. Both powers hope trade and investment will sustain national unity. For the first time, Jonathan Holslag identifies these objectives as new sources of rivalry and argues that China and India cannot grow without fierce contest.Though he recognizes that both countries wish to maintain stable relations, Holslag argues that success in implementing economic reform will give way to conflict. This rivalry is already tangible in Asia as a whole, where shifting patterns of economic influence have altered the balance of power and have led to shortsighted policies that undermine regional stability. Holslag also demonstrates that despite two decades of peace, mutual perceptions have become hostile, and a military game of tit-for-tat promises to diminish prospects for peace. Holslag therefore refutes the notion that development and interdependence lead to peace, and he does so by embedding rich empirical evidence within broader debates on international relations theory. His book is down-to-earth and realistic while also taking into account the complexities of internal policymaking. The result is a fascinating portrait of the complicated interaction among economic, political, military, and perceptional levels of diplomacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/hols1504240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231520973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231520973.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK